post_text: BIG NEWS!! Yesterday during a Zoom call with YSCS student athletes and their Coach, Tony the Tiger, @shaq and @candaceparker popped in and made a huge announcement! YSCS would be receiving a donation of $200,000 from Mission Tiger to help our school stay in the game when sports can finally resume next year! This donation will provide us with a new sports court on school grounds dedicated as a safe space for students to play and train, new uniforms and equipment, as well as cover the costs of facility fees and even entire seasons of league play. We are so thankful Mission Tiger and @kelloggsfrostedflakes!

post_text: This past week we focused on one of our Core values- Empathy. We were honored to have Holocaust survivor, Anneliese N. talk to us about her experiences during the Holocaust and how much strength it took her to get through that devastating time. She told us to be kind to those around us and emphasized the importance of treating others with respect. We also had a presentation by the ADL - Anti-Defamation League, who taught us how to build an inclusive and safe community where we can all thrive. Thank you, Anneliese and ADL for teaching us how to come together as a caring community and inspiring us to help others in our neighborhoods and across the world.

post_text: Last week, as part of our November Experience Month Expedition series, we sent a group of students on an adventure at Penn Museum where they discovered mummies, artifacts, and art from Ancient China, Japan, and Greece. Our students toured the expansive galleries and enjoyed an interactive lesson and group activity. At least two students were overheard having independent conversation and saying they‚Äôd like to be archaeologists. Moments like that capture the essence of why we host these trips for our scholars. Thank you to our friends @pennmuseum for their hospitality! Their partnership in shortening the experience gap for our students is greatly appreciated.

post_text: Instead of traditional quarterly conferences, we host Student-Led Conferences where our scholars speak directly with their families and teachers about their report card. This approach reinforces accountability and allows our students a more active role in their academic careers. It becomes their job to reflect on their first quarter assignments, grades, and behaviors and to design a plan that sets them up for success in the future. This family is all smiles because their 6th grade scholar received a 3.8 GPA, which qualifies her for Distinguished Honors, our school‚Äôs highest honors. üíôü¶Å

March 20, 2018 at 4:30 PM ¬∑

Due to the forecasted inclement weather, all School District of Philadelphia schools and administrative offices will be closed Wednesday, March 21, 2018. All after-school activities including all athletic programs and professional development sessions scheduled for Wednesday are canceled as well. All District early childhood centers will also be closed.

All School District building engineers are to report for work at their normal start time and further instructions will be sent to them.

The general public and media are urged to monitor the District website at www.philasd.org and our Twitter feed, @PHLschools, for further details. Updated information will also be posted on the District's Information Hotline at 215-400-INFO (4636).
